The stylized quantile regression plot

library(haven)

quantile1 <- read_dta("C:/Users/Dirk/OneDrive - Universitt Mnster/2. Master/4. Semester/Masterarbeit/Data/Plot Quantile Regression/quantile1.dta")
library(evd)
library(QuantifQuantile)

set.seed(85)
n <- 5000
X <- as.vector(quantile1$x)
Y <- as.vector(quantile1$y)
testN <- seq(10, 30, by = 5)
res <- QuantifQuantile(X, Y, testN = testN)
plot(res, ise = TRUE)

op <- par(family = "serif")
plot(X,Y)
points(c(rep(0,5)),res$hatq_opt[,1],col="red",pch=21,bg="red")
points(c(rep(0.5,5)),res$hatq_opt[,17],col="red",pch=21,bg="red")

points(c(rep(1.5,5)),res$hatq_opt[,50],col="red",pch=21,bg="red")
points(c(rep(2,5)),res$hatq_opt[,67],col="red",pch=21,bg="red")
points(c(rep(2.5,5)),res$hatq_opt[,83],col="red",pch=21,bg="red")

lm_x=c(0,0.5,1,1.5,2,2.5)

Total connectedness plot over time

# read the file of total connectedness and averaged lambda
f = read.csv("C:/Users/Dirk/OneDrive - Universitt Mnster/2. Master/4. Semester/Masterarbeit/Data/total_connectedness_and_averaged_lambda.csv")
dt = as.Date(f[, 1], format = "%Y-%m-%d")
total.c = as.vector(f[, 2])
average_lambda = as.vector(f[, 3])

library(imputeTS)
total.c= na_interpolation(total.c,option = "spline")

# scale the total connectedness and averaged lambda into 0 and 1
total.c = (total.c - min(total.c))/(max(total.c) - min(total.c))
average_lambda = (average_lambda - min(average_lambda))/(max(average_lambda) - min(average_lambda))
op <- par(family = "serif")
plot(dt, total.c, ylab = "", xlab = "", pch = 16, col = "white", cex.axis = 1.5, font.axis = 2.5)
tc_plot=smooth.spline(dt, total.c,spar = 0.8)
lines(tc_plot$x,tc_plot$y, lwd = 5, col = "blue")
dt_plot=smooth.spline(dt, average_lambda, df = 5, spar = 0.8)
lines(dt_plot$x,dt_plot$y, col = "black", lty = 2, 
      lwd = 5)
legend("topleft", box.lwd = 1, box.col = NA, bg = NA, 
       c("Gesamtvernetzung","Durchschnittliches Lambda"),,lty = c("solid","dashed"),lwd = 2, 
       cex = 1,col = c("blue","black"),y.intersp = 0.8)

The connectedness matrix with thresholding at time t

# apply a hard thresholding to make the major connections more clearly
con = ifelse(abs(con) >= ((1/40) * sum(con[order(con, decreasing = T)[1:36]])), 
             con, 0)

# plot a network based on the adjacency matrix 'con' after thresholding, so that
# we can see the directional connection caused by spillover effects among 100
# financial institutions.
plot_g = qgraph(con, groups = groups, layout = "groups", layoutScale = c(1.2, 1.2), 
                label.font = 1, label.cex = 1.85, shape = "circle", labels = names.fi, esize = 5, 
                maximum = max(con), color = rep("white",6), node.width = 0.8, label.cex = 1.85, label.color = col, 
                edge.color = col, curve = 1, border.width = 1.2, border.color = col, asize = 2.5)

text(x = -0.9, y = 1, labels = substitute(paste(d), list(d = as.character(dt[78]))),

f            = read.csv("total_in_and_out.csv")

total.in.it   = as.vector(f[, 5])/7

library(imputeTS)

total.in.sp= na_interpolation(total.in.sp,option = "spline")
total.in.sk= na_interpolation(total.in.sk,option = "spline")
